[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Since September 2024, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The **`content-visibility`** CSS property controls whether or not an element renders its contents at all, along with forcing a strong set of containments, allowing user agents to potentially omit large swathes of layout and rendering work until it becomes needed.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] It enables the user agent to skip an element's rendering work (including layout and painting) until it is needed — which makes the initial page load much faster.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The element's contents are laid out and rendered as normal.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The skipped contents must not be accessible to user-agent features, such as find-in-page, tab-order navigation, etc., nor be selectable or focusable.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] This is similar to giving the contents `display: none`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The element turns on layout containment, style containment, and paint containment.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] If the element is not relevant to the user, it also skips its contents.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Unlike hidden, the skipped contents must still be available as normal to user-agent features such as find-in-page, tab order navigation, etc., and must be focusable and selectable as normal.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Supporting browsers animate/transition `content-visibility` with a variation on the discrete animation type.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Discrete animation generally means that the property will flip between two values 50% of the way through the animation.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] In the case of `content-visibility`, however, the browser will flip between the two values to show the animated content for the entire animation duration.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] This behavior is useful for creating entry/exit animations where you want to, for example, remove some content from the DOM with `content-visibility: hidden`, but you want a smooth transition (such as a fade-out) rather than it disappearing immediately.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] When animating `content-visibility` with CSS transitions, `transition-behavior: allow-discrete` needs to be set on `content-visibility`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] This effectively enables `content-visibility` transitions.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Off-screen content within a `content-visibility: auto` property remains in the document object model and the accessibility tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] This allows improving page performance with `content-visibility: auto` without negatively impacting accessibility.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Since styles for off-screen content are not rendered, elements intentionally hidden with `display: none` or `visibility: hidden` *will still appear in the accessibility tree*.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] If you don't want an element to appear in the accessibility tree, use `aria-hidden="true"`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The following example shows the use of `content-visibility: auto` to skip painting and rendering of off-screen sections.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] When a `section` is out of the viewport then the painting of the content is skipped until the section comes close to the viewport, this helps with both load and interactions on the page.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The `contain-intrinsic-size` property adds a default size of 500px to the height and width of each `section` element.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] After a section is rendered, it will retain its rendered intrinsic size, even when it is scrolled out of the viewport.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The following example shows how to manage content visibility with JavaScript.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Using `content-visibility: hidden;` instead of `display: none;` preserves the rendering state of content when hidden and rendering is faster.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The `content-visibility` property is set on paragraphs that are direct children of elements with the `visible` and `hidden` classes.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] In our example, we can show and hide content in paragraphs depending on the CSS class of parent div elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] The `contain-intrinsic-size` property is included to represent the content size.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] This helps to reduce layout shift when content is hidden.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] In this example, we have a `<div>` element, the content of which can be toggled between shown and hidden by clicking or pressing any key.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] In the CSS we initially set `content-visibility: hidden;` on the `<div>` to hide its content.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] We then set up `@keyframes` animations and attach them to classes to show and hide the `<div>`, animating `content-visibility` and `color` so that you get a smooth animation effect as the content is shown/hidden.
[src:critical-rendering-path/content-visibility] Finally, we use JavaScript to apply the `.show` and `.hide` classes to the `<div>` as appropriate to apply the animations as it is toggled between shown and hidden states.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The Critical Rendering Path is the sequence of steps the browser goes through to convert the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript into pixels on the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Optimizing the critical render path improves render performance.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The critical rendering path includes the Document Object Model (DOM), CSS Object Model (CSSOM), render tree and layout.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The document object model is created as the HTML is parsed.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The HTML may request JavaScript, which may, in turn, alter the DOM.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The HTML includes or makes requests for styles, which in turn builds the CSS object model.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The browser engine combines the two to create the Render Tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Layout determines the size and location of everything on the page.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Once layout is determined, pixels are painted to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Optimizing the critical rendering path improves the time to first render.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Understanding and optimizing the critical rendering path is important to ensure reflows and repaints can happen at 60 frames per second, to ensure performant user interactions, and to avoid jank.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Web performance includes the server requests and responses, loading, scripting, rendering, layout, and the painting of the pixels to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] A request for a web page or app starts with an HTTP request.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The server sends a response containing the HTML.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The browser then begins parsing the HTML, converting the received bytes to the DOM tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The browser initiates requests every time it finds links to external resources, be it stylesheets, scripts, or embedded image references.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Some requests are blocking, which means the parsing of the rest of the HTML is halted until the imported asset is handled.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The browser continues to parse the HTML making requests and building the DOM, until it gets to the end, at which point it constructs the CSS object model.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] With the DOM and CSSOM complete, the browser builds the render tree, computing the styles for all the visible content.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] After the render tree is complete, layout occurs, defining the location and size of all the render tree elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Once complete, the page is rendered, or 'painted' on the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The HTML response turns into tokens which turns into nodes which turn into the DOM Tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] A single DOM node starts with a startTag token and ends with an endTag token.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Nodes contain all relevant information about the HTML element.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The information is described using tokens.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Nodes are connected into a DOM tree based on token hierarchy.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] If another set of startTag and endTag tokens come between a set of startTag and endTags, you have a node inside a node, which is how we define the hierarchy of the DOM tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The greater the number of nodes, the longer the following events in the critical rendering path will take.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] A few extra nodes won't make a big difference, but keep in mind that adding many extra nodes will impact performance.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The DOM contains all the content of the page.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The CSSOM contains all the information on how to style the DOM.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] CSSOM is similar to the DOM, but different.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] While the DOM construction is incremental, CSSOM is not.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] CSS is render blocking: the browser blocks page rendering until it receives and processes all the CSS.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] CSS is render blocking because rules can be overwritten, so the content can't be rendered until the CSSOM is complete.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] CSS has its own set of rules for identifying valid tokens.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Remember the C in CSS stands for 'Cascade'.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] As the parser converts tokens to nodes, descendant nodes will inherit some of the styles of the parent.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The incremental processing features don't apply to CSS like they do with HTML, because subsequent rules may override previous ones.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The CSS object model gets built as the CSS is parsed, but can't be used to build the render tree until it is completely parsed because styles that are going to be overwritten with later parsing should not be rendered to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] In terms of selector performance, less specific selectors are faster than more specific ones.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] For example, `.foo {}` is faster than `.bar .foo {}` because when the browser finds `.foo`, in the second scenario, it has to walk up the DOM to check if `.foo` has an ancestor `.bar`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The more specific tag requires more work from the browser, but this penalty is not likely worth optimizing around.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] If you measure the time it takes to parse CSS, you'll be amazed at how fast browsers truly are.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The more specific rule is more expensive because it has to traverse more nodes in the DOM tree - but that extra expense is generally minimal.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Specificity is likely not your lowest hanging fruit.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] When it comes to CSS, selector performance optimization improvements will only be in microseconds.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] There are other ways to optimize CSS, such as minification, and separating deferred CSS into non-blocking requests by using media queries.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The render tree captures both the content and the styles: the DOM and CSSOM trees are combined into the render tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] To construct the render tree, the browser checks every node, starting from root of the DOM tree, and determines which CSS rules are attached.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The render tree only captures visible content.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The head section (generally) doesn't contain any visible information, and is therefore not included in the render tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] If there's a `display: none;` set on an element, neither it, nor any of its descendants, are in the render tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Once the render tree is built, layout becomes possible.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Layout is dependent on the size of screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The layout step determines where and how the elements are positioned on the page, determining the width and height of each element, and where they are in relation to each other.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Block level elements, by definition, have a default width of 100% of the width of their parent.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] An element with a width of 50%, will be half of the width of its parent.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Unless otherwise defined, the body has a width of 100%, meaning it will be 100% of the width of the viewport.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] This width of the device impacts layout.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The viewport meta tag defines the width of the layout viewport, impacting the layout.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Without it, the browser uses the default viewport width, which on by-default full screen browsers is generally 960px.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] On by-default full screen browsers, like your phone's browser, by setting `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width">`, the width will be the width of the device instead of the default viewport width.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The device-width changes when a user rotates their phone between landscape and portrait mode.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Layout happens every time a device is rotated or browser is otherwise resized.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Layout performance is impacted by the DOM — the greater the number of nodes, the longer layout takes.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Layout can become a bottleneck, leading to jank if required during scrolling or other animations.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] While a 20ms delay on load or orientation change may be fine, it will lead to jank on animation or scroll.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Any time the render tree is modified, such as by added nodes, altered content, or updated box model styles on a node, layout occurs.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] To reduce the frequency and duration of layout events, batch updates and avoid animating box model properties.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The last step is painting the pixels to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Once the render tree is created and layout occurs, the pixels can be painted to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] After that, only impacted areas of the screen will be repainted, as browsers are optimized to repaint the minimum area required.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Paint time depends on what kind of updates are being applied to the render tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] While painting is a very fast process, and therefore likely not the most impactful place to focus on in improving performance, it is important to remember to allow for both layout and re-paint times when measuring how long an animation frame may take.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] The styles applied to each node increase the paint time, but removing style that increases the paint by 0.001ms may not give you the biggest bang for your optimization buck.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Then you can determine whether it should be an optimization priority.
[src:critical-rendering-path/critical-rendering-path] Improve page load speed by prioritizing which resources get loaded, controlling the order in which they are loaded, and reducing the file sizes of those resources.
[src:critical-rendering-path/css-object-model] The **CSS Object Model** is a set of APIs allowing the manipulation of CSS from JavaScript.
[src:critical-rendering-path/css-object-model] It is much like the DOM, but for the CSS rather than the HTML.
[src:critical-rendering-path/css-object-model] It allows users to read and modify CSS style dynamically.
[src:critical-rendering-path/css-object-model] The values of CSS are represented untyped, that is using `String` objects.
[src:critical-rendering-path/css-object-model] Several other interfaces are also extended by the CSSOM-related specifications: `Document`, `Window`, `Element`, `HTMLElement`, `HTMLImageElement`, `Range`, `MouseEvent`, and `SVGElement`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/css-object-model] All these features have been added little by little over the years to the different browsers: it was a quite complex process that can't be summarized in a simple table.
[src:critical-rendering-path/css-object-model] Please refer to the specific interfaces for its availability.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) connects web pages to scripts or programming languages by representing the structure of a document—such as the HTML representing a web page—in memory.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Usually it refers to JavaScript, even though modeling HTML, SVG, or XML documents as objects are not part of the core JavaScript language.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] With them, you can change the document's structure, style, or content.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Nodes can also have event handlers attached to them.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface for web documents.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] It represents the page so that programs can change the document structure, style, and content.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The DOM represents the document as nodes and objects; that way, programming languages can interact with the page.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] A web page is a document that can be either displayed in the browser window or as the HTML source.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] In both cases, it is the same document but the Document Object Model (DOM) representation allows it to be manipulated.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] As an object-oriented representation of the web page, it can be modified with a scripting language such as JavaScript.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] All of the properties, methods, and events available for manipulating and creating web pages are organized into objects.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] For example, the `document` object that represents the document itself, any `table` objects that implement the `HTMLTableElement` DOM interface for accessing HTML tables, and so forth, are all objects.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The DOM is built using multiple APIs that work together.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The core DOM defines the entities describing any document and the objects within it.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] This is expanded upon as needed by other APIs that add new features and capabilities to the DOM.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] For example, the HTML DOM API adds support for representing HTML documents to the core DOM, and the SVG API adds support for representing SVG documents.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] A **DOM tree** is a tree structure whose nodes represent an HTML or XML document's contents.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Each HTML or XML document has a DOM tree representation.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Although the above tree is similar to the above document's DOM tree, they're not identical, as the actual DOM tree preserves whitespace.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When a web browser parses an HTML document, it builds a DOM tree and then uses it to display the document.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The previous short example, like nearly all examples, is JavaScript.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] That is to say, it is *written* in JavaScript, but *uses* the DOM to access the document and its elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The DOM is not a programming language, but without it, the JavaScript language wouldn't have any model or notion of web pages, HTML documents, SVG documents, and their component parts.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The document as a whole, the head, tables within the document, table headers, text within the table cells, and all other elements in a document are parts of the document object model for that document.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] They can all be accessed and manipulated using the DOM and a scripting language like JavaScript.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The DOM is not part of the JavaScript language, but is instead a Web API used to build websites.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] JavaScript can also be used in other contexts.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] For example, Node.js runs JavaScript programs on a computer, but provides a different set of APIs, and the DOM API is not a core part of the Node.js runtime.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The DOM was designed to be independent of any particular programming language, making the structural representation of the document available from a single, consistent API.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] For more information on what technologies are involved in writing JavaScript on the web, see JavaScript technologies overview.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] You don't have to do anything special to begin using the DOM.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] You use the API directly in JavaScript from within what is called a *script*, a program run by a browser.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When you create a script, whether inline in a `<script>` element or included in the web page, you can immediately begin using the API for the `document` or `window` objects to manipulate the document itself, or any of the various elements in the web page (the descendant elements of the document).
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] As it is generally not recommended to mix the structure of the page (written in HTML) and manipulation of the DOM (written in JavaScript), the JavaScript parts will be grouped together here, and separated from the HTML.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] This guide is about the objects and the actual *things* you can use to manipulate the DOM hierarchy.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] There are many points where understanding how these work can be confusing.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] For example, the object representing the HTML `form` element gets its `name` property from the `HTMLFormElement` interface but its `className` property from the `HTMLElement` interface.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] In both cases, the property you want is in that form object.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] But the relationship between objects and the interfaces that they implement in the DOM can be confusing, and so this section attempts to say a little something about the actual interfaces in the DOM specification and how they are made available.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Many objects implement several different interfaces.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The table object, for example, implements a specialized `HTMLTableElement` interface, which includes such methods as `createCaption` and `insertRow`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] But since it's also an HTML element, `table` implements the `Element` interface described in the DOM `Element` Reference chapter.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] And finally, since an HTML element is also, as far as the DOM is concerned, a node in the tree of nodes that make up the object model for an HTML or XML page, the table object also implements the more basic `Node` interface, from which `Element` derives.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When you get a reference to a `table` object, as in the following example, you routinely use all three of these interfaces interchangeably on the object, perhaps without knowing it.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] This page tries to describe the various objects and types in simple terms.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] But there are a number of different data types being passed around the API that you should be aware of.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The following table briefly describes these data types.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] There are also some common terminology considerations to keep in mind.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] It's common to refer to any `Attr` node as an `attribute`, for example, and to refer to an array of DOM nodes as a `nodeList`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] You'll find these terms and others to be introduced and used throughout the documentation.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The `document` and `window` objects are the objects whose interfaces you generally use most often in DOM programming.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] In simple terms, the `window` object represents something like the browser, and the `document` object is the root of the document itself.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] `Element` inherits from the generic `Node` interface, and together these two interfaces provide many of the methods and properties you use on individual elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] These elements may also have specific interfaces for dealing with the kind of data those elements hold, as in the `table` object example in the previous section.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The Document Object Model has been highly simplified.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] To achieve this, the following interfaces in the different DOM level 3 or earlier specifications have been removed.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] They are no longer available to web developers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] A document containing HTML is described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the HTML specification to include various HTML-specific features.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `HTMLElement` and various subclasses, each representing one of (or a family of closely related) elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The HTML DOM API provides access to various browser features such as tabs and windows, CSS styles and stylesheets, browser history, etc.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] These interfaces are discussed further in the HTML DOM API documentation.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Similarly, a document containing SVG is also described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the SVG specification to include various SVG-specific features.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `SVGElement` and various subclasses, each representing an element or a family of closely related elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] These interfaces are discussed further in the SVG API documentation.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<textarea>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When the user clicks the first button we set some text in the `<textarea>`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When the user clicks the second button we clear the text.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<div>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When the user clicks the first button we create a new element and add it as a child of the `<div>`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When the user clicks the second button we remove the child element.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Suppose the author wants to change the header of the document in What is a DOM tree? and write two paragraphs instead of one.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] You can create the tree in What is a DOM tree? entirely in JavaScript too.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] This example demonstrates how events fire and are handled in the DOM in a very simple way.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] When the BODY of this HTML document loads, an event listener is registered with the top row of the TABLE.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The event listener handles the event by executing the function stopEvent, which changes the value in the bottom cell of the table.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] However, stopEvent also calls an event object method, `event.stopPropagation`, which keeps the event from bubbling any further up into the DOM.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Note that the table itself has an `onclick` event handler that ought to display a message when the table is clicked.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] But the stopEvent method has stopped propagation, and so after the data in the table is updated, the event phase is effectively ended, and an alert box is displayed to confirm this.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] This example uses DOM methods to display all the properties of the `click` event object and their values in a table.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] It also shows a useful technique of using a `for...in` loop to iterate over the properties of an object to get their values.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] The properties of event objects differs greatly between browsers, the WHATWG DOM Standard lists the standard properties, however many browsers have extended these greatly.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] Put the following code into a blank text file and load it into a variety of browsers, you'll be surprised at the different number and names of properties.
[src:critical-rendering-path/document-object-model] You might also like to add some elements in the page and call this function from different event handlers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Users want web experiences with content that is fast to load and smooth to interact with.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Therefore, a developer should strive to achieve these two goals.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] To understand how to improve performance and perceived performance, it helps to understand how the browser works.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Fast sites provide better user experiences.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Users want and expect web experiences with content that is fast to load and smooth to interact with.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Two major issues in web performance are issues having to do with latency and issues having to do with the fact that for the most part, browsers are single-threaded.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Latency is the biggest threat to our ability to ensure a fast-loading page.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] It is the developers' goal to make the site load as fast as possible — or at least *appear* to load super fast — so the user gets the requested information as quickly as possible.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Network latency is the time it takes to transmit bytes over the air to computers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Web performance is what we have to do to make the page load as quickly as possible.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] For the most part, browsers are considered single-threaded.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] That is, they execute a task from beginning to end before taking up another task.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] For smooth interactions, the developer's goal is to ensure performant site interactions, from smooth scrolling to being responsive to touch.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Render time is key, ensuring the main thread can complete all the work we throw at it and still always be available to handle user interactions.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Web performance can be improved by understanding the single-threaded nature of the browser and minimizing the main thread's responsibilities, where possible and appropriate, to ensure rendering is smooth and responses to interactions are immediate.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] One of the goals of web performance is to minimize the amount of time navigation takes to complete.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In ideal conditions, this usually doesn't take too long, but latency and bandwidth are foes that can cause delays.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The first step of navigating to a web page is finding where the assets for that page are located.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If you navigate to `https://example.com`, the HTML page is located on the server with IP address of `93.184.216.34`.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If you've never visited this site, a DNS lookup must happen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Your browser requests a DNS lookup, which is eventually fielded by a name server, which in turn responds with an IP address.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] After this initial request, the IP will likely be cached for a time, which speeds up subsequent requests by retrieving the IP address from the cache instead of contacting a name server again.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] DNS lookups usually only need to be done once per hostname for a page load.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] However, DNS lookups must be done for each unique hostname the requested page references.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If your fonts, images, scripts, ads, and metrics all have different hostnames, a DNS lookup will have to be made for each one.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] This can be problematic for performance, particularly on mobile networks.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] When a user is on a mobile network, each DNS lookup has to go from the phone to the cell tower to reach an authoritative DNS server.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The distance between a phone, a cell tower, and the name server can add significant latency.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Once the IP address is known, the browser sets up a connection to the server via a TCP three-way handshake.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] This mechanism is designed so that two entities attempting to communicate — in this case the browser and web server — can negotiate the parameters of the network TCP socket connection before transmitting data, often over HTTPS.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] TCP's three-way handshaking technique is often referred to as "SYN-SYN-ACK" — or more accurately SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK — because there are three messages transmitted by TCP to negotiate and start a TCP session between two computers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Yes, this means three more messages back and forth between each server, and the request has yet to be made.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] For secure connections established over HTTPS, another "handshake" is required.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] This handshake, or rather the TLS negotiation, determines which cipher will be used to encrypt the communication, verifies the server, and establishes that a secure connection is in place before beginning the actual transfer of data.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] This requires five more round trips to the server before the request for content is actually sent.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] While making the connection secure adds time to the page load, a secure connection is worth the latency expense, as the data transmitted between the browser and the web server cannot be decrypted by a third party.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] After the eight round trips to the server, the browser is finally able to make the request.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Once we have an established connection to a web server, the browser sends an initial HTTP `GET` request on behalf of the user, which for websites is most often an HTML file.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Once the server receives the request, it will reply with relevant response headers and the contents of the HTML.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] This response for this initial request contains the first byte of data received.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Time to First Byte (TTFB) is the time between when the user made the request — say by clicking on a link — and the receipt of this first packet of HTML.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The first chunk of content is usually 14KB of data.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In our example above, the request is definitely less than 14KB, but the linked resources aren't requested until the browser encounters the links during parsing, described below.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] TCP packets are split into segments during transmission.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Because TCP guarantees the sequence of packets, the server must receive an acknowledgment from the client in the form of an ACK packet after sending a certain number of segments.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If the server waits for an ACK after each segment, that will result in frequent ACKs from the client and may increase transmission time, even in the case of a low-load network.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] On the other hand, sending too many segments at once can lead to the problem that in a busy network the client will not be able to receive the segments and will just keep responding with ACKs for a long time, and the server will have to keep re-sending the segments.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In order to balance the number of transmitted segments, the TCP slow start algorithm is used to gradually increase the amount of transmitted data until the maximum network bandwidth can be determined, and to reduce the amount of transmitted data in case of high network load.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The number of segments to be transmitted is controlled by the value of the congestion window (CWND), which can be initialized to 1, 2, 4, or 10 MSS (MSS is 1500 bytes over the Ethernet protocol).
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] That value is the number of bytes to send, upon receipt of which the client must send an ACK.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If an ACK is received, then the CWND value will be doubled, and so the server will be able to send more segments the next time.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If instead no ACK is received, then the CWND value will be halved.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] That mechanism thus achieves a balance between sending too many segments, and sending too few.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Once the browser receives the first chunk of data, it can begin parsing the information received.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Parsing is the step the browser takes to turn the data it receives over the network into the DOM and CSSOM, which is used by the renderer to paint a page to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The DOM is the internal representation of the markup for the browser.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The DOM is also exposed and can be manipulated through various APIs in JavaScript.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Even if the requested page's HTML is larger than the initial 14KB packet, the browser will begin parsing and attempting to render an experience based on the data it has.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] This is why it's important for web performance optimization to include everything the browser needs to start rendering a page, or at least a template of the page — the CSS and HTML needed for the first render — in the first 14KB.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] But before anything is rendered to the screen, the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript have to be parsed.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] We describe five steps in the critical rendering path.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The first step is processing the HTML markup and building the DOM tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] HTML parsing involves tokenization and tree construction.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] HTML tokens include start and end tags, as well as attribute names and values.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If the document is well-formed, parsing it is straightforward and faster.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The parser parses tokenized input into the document, building up the document tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The DOM tree describes the content of the document.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The `<html>` element is the first element and root node of the document tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The tree reflects the relationships and hierarchies between different elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Elements nested within other elements are child nodes.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The greater the number of DOM nodes, the longer it takes to construct the DOM tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] When the parser finds non-blocking resources, such as an image, the browser will request those resources and continue parsing.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Parsing can continue when a CSS file is encountered, but `<script>` elements — particularly those without an `async` or `defer` attribute — block rendering, and pause the parsing of HTML.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Though the browser's preload scanner hastens this process, excessive scripts can still be a significant bottleneck.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] While the browser builds the DOM tree, this process occupies the main thread.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] As this happens, the *preload scanner* will parse through the content available and request high-priority resources like CSS, JavaScript, and web fonts.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Thanks to the preload scanner, we don't have to wait until the parser finds a reference to an external resource to request it.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] It will retrieve resources in the background so that by the time the main HTML parser reaches the requested assets, they may already be in flight or have been downloaded.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The optimizations the preload scanner provides reduce blockages.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In this example, while the main thread is parsing the HTML and CSS, the preload scanner will find the scripts and image, and start downloading them as well.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] To ensure the script doesn't block the process, add the `async` attribute, or the `defer` attribute if JavaScript parsing and execution order is important.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Waiting to obtain CSS doesn't block HTML parsing or downloading, but it does block JavaScript because JavaScript is often used to query CSS properties' impact on elements.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The second step in the critical rendering path is processing CSS and building the CSSOM tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The CSS object model is similar to the DOM.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The browser converts the CSS rules into a map of styles it can understand and work with.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The browser goes through each rule set in the CSS, creating a tree of nodes with parent, child, and sibling relationships based on the CSS selectors.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] As with HTML, the browser needs to convert the received CSS rules into something it can work with.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Hence, it repeats the HTML-to-object process, but for the CSS.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The CSSOM tree includes styles from the user agent style sheet.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The browser begins with the most general rule applicable to a node and recursively refines the computed styles by applying more specific rules.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In other words, it cascades the property values.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Building the CSSOM is very, very fast, and this build time information is not displayed in the developer tools.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Rather, the "Recalculate Style" in developer tools shows the total time it takes to parse CSS, construct the CSSOM tree, and recursively calculate computed styles.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In terms of web performance, there are many better ways to invest optimization effort, as the total time to create the CSSOM is generally less than the time it takes for one DNS lookup.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] While the CSS is being parsed and the CSSOM created, other assets, including JavaScript files, are downloading (thanks to the preload scanner).
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] JavaScript is parsed, compiled, and interpreted.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The scripts are parsed into abstract syntax trees.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Some browser engines take the abstract syntax trees and pass them into a compiler, outputting bytecode.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] This is known as JavaScript compilation.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Most of the code is interpreted on the main thread, but there are exceptions such as code run in web workers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The browser also builds an accessibility tree that assistive devices use to parse and interpret content.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The accessibility object model (AOM) is like a semantic version of the DOM.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The browser updates the accessibility tree when the DOM is updated.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The accessibility tree is not modifiable by assistive technologies themselves.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Until the AOM is built, the content is not accessible to screen readers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Rendering steps include style, layout, paint, and in some cases compositing.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The CSSOM and DOM trees created in the parsing step are combined into a render tree which is then used to compute the layout of every visible element, which is then painted to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In some cases, content can be promoted to its own layer and composited, improving performance by painting portions of the screen on the GPU instead of the CPU, freeing up the main thread.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The third step in the critical rendering path is combining the DOM and CSSOM into a render tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The computed style tree, or render tree, construction starts with the root of the DOM tree, traversing each visible node.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Elements that aren't going to be displayed, like the `<head>` element and its children and any nodes with `display: none`, such as the `script { display: none; }` you will find in user agent stylesheets, are not included in the render tree as they will not appear in the rendered output.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Nodes with `visibility: hidden` applied are included in the render tree, as they do take up space.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] As we have not given any directives to override the user agent default, the `script` node in our code example above will not be included in the render tree.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Each visible node has its CSSOM rules applied to it.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The render tree holds all the visible nodes with content and computed styles — matching up all the relevant styles to every visible node in the DOM tree, and determining, based on the CSS cascade, what the computed styles are for each node.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The fourth step in the critical rendering path is running layout on the render tree to compute the geometry of each node.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] *Layout* is the process by which the dimensions and location of all the nodes in the render tree are determined, plus the determination of the size and position of each object on the page.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] *Reflow* is any subsequent size and position determination of any part of the page or the entire document.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Once the render tree is built, layout commences.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The render tree identified which nodes are displayed (even if invisible) along with their computed styles, but not the dimensions or location of each node.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] To determine the exact size and position of each object, the browser starts at the root of the render tree and traverses it.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] On the web page, almost everything is a box.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Different devices and different desktop preferences mean an unlimited number of differing viewport sizes.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In this phase, taking the viewport size into consideration, the browser determines what the sizes of all the different boxes are going to be on the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Taking the size of the viewport as its base, layout generally starts with the body, laying out the sizes of all the body's descendants, with each element's box model properties, providing placeholder space for replaced elements it doesn't know the dimensions of, such as our image.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The first time the size and position of each node is determined is called *layout*.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Subsequent recalculations of *layout* are called *reflows*.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In our example, suppose the initial layout occurs before the image is returned.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Since we didn't declare the dimensions of our image, there will be a reflow once the image dimensions are known.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The last step in the critical rendering path is painting the individual nodes to the screen, the first occurrence of which is called the first Meaningful Paint.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In the painting or rasterization phase, the browser converts each box calculated in the layout phase to actual pixels on the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Painting involves drawing every visual part of an element to the screen, including text, colors, borders, shadows, and replaced elements like buttons and images.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] The browser needs to do this super quickly.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] To ensure smooth scrolling and animation, everything occupying the main thread, including calculating styles, along with reflow and paint, must take the browser less than 16.67ms to accomplish.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] At 2048 x 1536, the iPad has over 3,145,000 pixels to be painted to the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] That is a lot of pixels that have to be painted very quickly.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] To ensure repainting can be done even faster than the initial paint, the drawing to the screen is generally broken down into several layers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If this occurs, then compositing is necessary.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Painting can break the elements in the layout tree into layers.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Promoting content into layers on the GPU (instead of the main thread on the CPU) improves paint and repaint performance.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] There are specific properties and elements that instantiate a layer, including `<video>` and `<canvas>`, and any element which has the CSS properties of `opacity`, a 3D `transform`, `will-change`, and a few others.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] These nodes will be painted onto their own layer, along with their descendants, unless a descendant necessitates its own layer for one (or more) of the above reasons.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Layers do improve performance but are expensive when it comes to memory management, so should not be overused as part of web performance optimization strategies.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] When sections of the document are drawn in different layers, overlapping each other, compositing is necessary to ensure they are drawn to the screen in the right order and the content is rendered correctly.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] As the page continues to load assets, reflows can happen (recall our example image that arrived late).
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] A reflow sparks a repaint and a re-composite.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Had we defined the dimensions of our image, no reflow would have been necessary, and only the layer that needed to be repainted would be repainted, and composited if necessary.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] But we didn't include the image dimensions!
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] When the image is obtained from the server, the rendering process goes back to the layout steps and restarts from there.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Once the main thread is done painting the page, you would think we would be "all set." That isn't necessarily the case.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If the load includes JavaScript, that was correctly deferred, and only executed after the `onload` event fires, the main thread might be busy, and not available for scrolling, touch, and other interactions.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] Time to Interactive (TTI) is the measurement of how long it took from that first request which led to the DNS lookup and TCP connection to when the page is interactive — interactive being the point in time after the First Contentful Paint when the page responds to user interactions within 50ms.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] If the main thread is occupied parsing, compiling, and executing JavaScript, it is not available and therefore not able to respond to user interactions in a timely (less than 50ms) fashion.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In our example, maybe the image loaded quickly, but perhaps the `another-script.js` file was 2MB and our user's network connection was slow.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In this case, the user would see the page super quickly, but wouldn't be able to scroll without jank until the script was downloaded, parsed, and executed.
[src:critical-rendering-path/how-browsers-work] In this example, JavaScript execution took over 1.5 seconds, and the main thread was fully occupied that entire time, unresponsive to click events or screen taps.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] A **browser engine** (also known as a **layout engine** or **rendering engine**) is a core software component of every major web browser.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] The primary job of a browser engine is to transform HTML documents and other resources of a web page into an interactive visual representation on a user's device.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] Besides "browser engine", two other related terms are commonly used: "layout engine" and "rendering engine".
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] In theory, layout and rendering (or "painting") could be handled by different engines.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] In practice, however, these components are tightly coupled and rarely encountered on their own outside of the browser engine.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] In addition to layout and rendering, a browser engine enforces the security policy between documents, handles navigation through hyperlinks and data submitted through forms, and implements the document object model (DOM) exposed to scripts associated with the document.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] To provide a wide range of dynamic behavior for web pages, every major browser supports JavaScript.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] However, JavaScript is implemented as a separate JavaScript engine, which has enabled its usage elsewhere.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] In a browser, the two engines are coordinated via the DOM and Web IDL bindings.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] Browser engines are also used in non-browser applications.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] An email client needs one to display HTML email.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] Beginning in the 2010s, many apps have been created with the frameworks based on Google's Chromium project; each of these standalone apps functions much like a web app.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] The layout of a web page is typically specified by Cascading Style Sheets (CSS).
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] Each style sheet is a series of rules for how the page should be presented.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] For example, some rules specify typography details, such as font, color, and text size, while others determine the placement of images.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] The engine combines all relevant CSS rules to calculate precise graphical coordinates and pixel values for the visual representation it will paint on the screen.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] The engine updates the visual representation in response to new events, including the user scrolling the page, content being asynchronously fetched, video playback, and canvas animations.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] It also may begin rendering before a page's resources are downloaded, which can result in visual changes as more data is received, such as images being gradually filled in or a flash of unstyled content.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] The following chart shows the duration of active development (when relevant new web standards continue to be added) for each engine in this section.
[src:critical-rendering-path/web-browser-engine] Note that Gecko, WebKit, and Blink are still actively developed.
